Rival Somali faction leaders meet in Mogadishu . Rival Somali faction leaders Hussein Aideed and Ali Mahdi Mohamed met on Thursday in a bid to solve the differences between them and bring peace to shattered Mogadishu . The two leaders met for 90 minutes with committees from both factions and , according to a delegate at the talks , accepted an agenda for negotiations on how to end their power struggle . It was the fourth meeting between Ali Mahdi , who is based in North Mogadishu and Aideed since he took over at the death of his father as the main faction chief in South Mogadishu last August . Aideed was elected by supporters as president of Somalia and heads a government rejected by Ali Mahdi and allied factions . Somalia has had no central government and has been torn apart by civil war since 1991 . 
